properties.headline: Flood Watch issued February 1 at 3:24AM PST until February 2 at 10:00AM PST by NWS Seattle WA
properties.description:
The Flood Watch continues for

* Portions of northwest Washington and west central Washington,
including the following counties, in northwest Washington,
Clallam, Grays Harbor, Jefferson, Kitsap, Mason, Skagit, and
Whatcom. In west central Washington, King, Lewis, Pierce,
Snohomish, and Thurston.

* Through Sunday morning

* The second round of rain moved into the northern portion of
Western Washington last night. The first round of rain Friday
brought 2 to 5 inches over the Olympics, 1 to 3 inches over the
Cascades, and up to an inch on the lowlands. In the second round
in the last six hours another 1 to 2 inches has been reported in
the Olympics and the Northern and Central Cascades. Another 1 to
2 inches is forecast for the Cascades this morning with lesser
amounts in the Olympics. The cold front will move south today
with the heavier rain moving into the South Cascades later this
morning into the early afternoon hours. Snow levels in the 4500
to 5500 foot range ahead of the front will lower to 2500 to 3500
feet behind the front. Precipitation rates will decrease
significantly behind the front.

Numerous rivers from King County northward are already flooding
or will be above flood stage later today. Rivers that are or
will be flooding, the flooding is expected to be in the minor
to moderate category.

Heavy rainfall may also cause periods of minor urban flooding.
properties.instruction:
A Flood Watch means there is a potential for flooding based on
current forecasts.

You should monitor latest forecasts and be alert for possible
Flood Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be
prepared to take action should flooding develop.

Latest river forecasts available at
water.weather.gov/ahps2/index.php?wfo=sew

NWSheadline: FLOOD WATCH REMAINS IN EFFECT THROUGH SUNDAY MORNING
